Why (b & 1)?

Check last bit.

Example:

13 = 1101
13 & 1
1

Example:

6 = 110
6 & 1
0

Meaning:

odd number -> last bit 1
even number -> last bit 0
Why b >>= 1?

Right shift by 1.

Example:

1101

becomes

110

which is:

13 -> 6

Essentially:

b /= 2
Why a = a*a?

Because we are generating:

2
4
16
256
...

which are:

2^1
2^2
2^4
2^8
...

Exactly the powers needed by binary decomposition.

Visual Summary
while(b>0){

    if((b&1)==1)
        ans*=a;

    a*=a;

    b>>=1;
}

Think:

Take current power if bit is 1.

Move to next power.

Move to next bit.
Why do we need MOD every time?

Without:

(ans*a)%MOD

numbers become enormous:

2^100000

which won't fit in any datatype.

Modulo keeps values bounded.

